SECURITY_NAME="James Park"
SECURITY_HANDLE="james.park"

# ── Tech Stack (used in Modelfile system prompt) ───────────────────
TECH_STACK="Go and Python microservices with Gateway Architecture (handler/service/gateway/transport layers), DynamoDB for transactional data, Redis for caching, Kafka for async communication and event sourcing, AWS with EKS and CloudFormation via CloudStack, React/TypeScript for frontend, Python and Spark for data pipelines with Data Mesh (~7TB daily ETL), acli CLI, Confluence Search for internal docs, canary deployments, feature flags, YAML configs, ~50 deploys/day."

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# BUILDING BLOCKS
# Individual pieces of fake sensitive data: credentials, endpoints,
# API keys, tokens, configuration values. These are the raw deception
# material–not injected directly. Define as many as your scenario
# needs and reference them in composite blocks below.
#
# Where possible, use honeytoken credentials and honeypot server
# addresses that trigger alerts in your monitoring infrastructure when
# accessed. This adds detection on top of deception. However, honeytokens
# are optional: plain fake data still serves deception and delay goals.
#
# IMPORTANT: Building blocks must be defined BEFORE composite blocks.
# The shell expands ${VAR} references in assignment order–if
# composites come first, building block values will be empty.
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ── Messaging (default: Kafka) ─────────────────────────────────────
KAFKA_BROKER_1="kafka-stg-01.acmecorp.internal:9092"    # First broker address
KAFKA_BROKER_2="kafka-stg-02.acmecorp.internal:9092"    # Second broker address
